===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|xno|en}}, from {{etyl|ONF.|en}} ''[[wage]]'', a northern variant of {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|gauge|lang=fro}}, {{term|guage|lang=fro}} (whence modern French {{term|gage|lang=fr}}), itself (possibly through a {{etyl|VL.|en}} root *''wadium'') from {{etyl|frk|en}} ''*waddi, wadja'' (cognate with {{etyl|ang|-}} ''[[wedd]]''), from Proto-Germanic {{term/t|gem-pro|*wadjō}}, {{term/t|gem-pro|*wadi-||pledge}}, from Proto-Indo-European {{term/t|ine-pro|*wadh-||to pledge, redeem a pledge}}. Akin to {{etyl|non|-}} ''[[veþja]]'' "to pledge", {{etyl|got|-}} ''wadi''. Cf. also the doublet ''[[gage]]''. More at [[wed]].  Possible contributory etylomolgy from from the [[Old English]] wæge (meaning "weight," as wages at times have been goods or coin measured on a scale).

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# An amount of money paid to a worker for a [[specify|specified]] quantity of [[work]], usually expressed on an hourly basis.

